column4: <content>66. Kirmes von Hoboken. [doorstreept]: 'Neu 79. My N°'; Mention at end after Gate of St. George.</content>

<parts.title>[recto] Ad [addendum] 66. Neuerdings will Louis Lebeer, in Miscellanea Leo van Puyvelde, Brüssel 1949, p. 99ff. [...]; [verso] 66. Kirmes von Hoboken erworben von Lord Lee of Fareham! Look up.</parts.title>

<parts.title>[Addendum] 110. Witt Library. P.B.I Genre Outdoor without Dancing. Works of Mercy.: 1) Fétis Sale, Brussels, Nov. 1908, N° 12, Bois, 43 x 57 cm. Signé P.Brevghel (sic!); 2) Private Coll. Holland. Exh. de Boer 1934, N° 22, Panel, 42 x 57 cm.</parts.title>
<parts.title>[Addendum] 110. Witt Library. Seven Deeds of Mercy. Harrack Coll. Vienna, Ph.</parts.title>

<parts.title>[recto] Ad [Addendum] 110. Witt Library. P.B.II. The Seven Acts of Mercy (from Matthew XXV): 1) Benedict Sale, Parke-Bernet, N.Y. 14-III-1951, N° 79, cradled panel, 163/4 x 231/4 in. Signed P. BR.; [toegevoegde vermelding]: 'F.G. 1) is not II Harrack for Harrich see 2)';  believed to be identical with one recorded in Bénézit, Dictionary des peintres 1924, vol. I, p. 776, as coming from the coll. Harrack of Vienna; [verso] Gal. Harrack, Vienna. exh. St. Lucas Gal. Vienna 1935, N°52, Holz, 42 x 59 cm. Sig. unten rechts P. Brueghel; 3) Henry Schenck-Stainford (U.S.A.) Exh. Antwerp 1930, N° 62, Bois, 43 x 58,5 cm. Signé en bas à droite: P. Braghel [sic]; 4) Sale Fiévez, Brussels, 8 May 1929, N° 32, Bois, 42,5 x57,5 cm au vente Musée Kemps, Anvers, mai 1898, N° 69.</parts.title>

<parts.title>Ad [Addendum] 111. Witt Library. P. Balten. Photographer of M%assacre of Innocents (the second composition) inscribed on mount: 'P.BALTEN (?).' Old Photograph by Cooper & Humphreys.</parts.title>
<parts.title>Ad [Addendum] 111. Rijksbureau. Kindermord: Andere Komposition mit fliehende Frau, Antw. Mus. (Photo Bruckmann) Sehr viele Kopien.</parts.title>

<parts.title>Ad [Addendum] 112?. Under P.B.I. Art certainly P.B.II invenit. Peasant wedding outdoor with hous ein background on the left the dishes on long board (like in Vienna Wedding) in cnetre people on the ground, on the right table (like in Vienna Wedding) with the [?] and the bagpiper.: 1) coll. Prince Serge Koudecheff à St. Petersbourg. Pieter Breughel (1564-1638) 'La Kermess', 43 x 69; 2) Sale, Lepke, Berlin, 11-2-1913, N° 126, P.B 1564-1635 (Bauern Hochzeit, rechtsunter signiert, Holz, 42 x 72 cm.</parts.title>

<parts.title>[Addendum] 112? Witt Library. Under P.B.I. Kermesse (certainly composition by P.BII) with Peasants dancing round maypole: 1) Verrier Sale, Brussels, Fiévez, 8-9 Dec. 1924, N° 27 (certficat Friedländer) 13. 50 x75; 2) Grossmann Sale, Munich 1902, Holz, 54 x 74 Unten links bezeichnet P. Breughel but [?] coarse then!; 3) With a tree added on the left. Greenstreet Exh. P. Brueghel, Dieter [?] Photo F.B. Photo Cooper.</parts.title>
<parts.title>66. LEBEER, Louis, La Kermesse d'Hoboken in: Miscellanea Leo van Puyvelde, Brüssel, 1949, pp. 99-106.</parts.title>
